I met an error when trying to use a concatenated value consisting of a parameter and a batch input. Following code reproduces the error:
```c++
Model m;
LookupParameter lp(m.add_lookup_parameters(10, {20}));
Parameter pp(m.add_parameters({30}));
ComputationGraph cg;
auto i1 = lookup(cg, lp, {1, 2, 3});
auto i2 = parameter(cg, pp);
auto i3 = concatenate({i1, i2});
auto i4 = transpose(i3) * i3;
auto i5 = sum_batches(i4);
cg.forward(i5);
cg.backward(i5);
```
I guess this code should work, but it dies due to an Eigen assertion error when the program reached at `cg.backward()`. If I swapped the 6th line for `i2 = input(cg, {30}, vector<float>(30));` then it looks to be working fine.

I couldn't find an easy way to turn off searching and pagination dynamically so I modified the datatableview.js file as follows:

```
...
$(function () {
    if (datatableview.auto_initialize) {
        var opts = {
            "searching": false,
            "paging": false
        };
        datatableview.initialize($('.datatable'), opts);
    }
}
```

Is it possible to expose the datatableview.initialize() opts parameter?  If not I think it would be really useful if the existing DatatableView.datatable_options dictionary could add data properties to the html table which the datatableview.js file could detect for simple boolean flags like searching and paging.

Thanks again,
